attributes.magic: ELF 32-bit LSB executable, ARM, EABI4 version 1 (SYSV), statically linked, with debug_info, not stripped

threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: This ELF binary is a sophisticated DDoS (Distributed Denial of Service) botnet agent, likely a variant of the Mirai family or similar IoT malware (indicated by 'aisuru' and 'wuhan' function suffixes). It features multiple flooding vectors including TCP (SYN, ACK, STOMP, XMAS), UDP (HEXFLOOD, VSE, DNS), ICMP, and GRE. Key malicious behaviors include: 1) A 'botnet killer' mechanism in 'killer_init' and 'kill_duplicate_connections' that scans /proc/net/tcp to identify and terminate competing malware processes; 2) C2 communication with a hardcoded IP (147.135.3.192); 3) Process name obfuscation and hiding using prctl; 4) Use of raw sockets for manual packet header construction and checksum calculation; and 5) Watchdog maintenance to ensure persistence. Relevant IOCs include the C2 IP 147.135.3.192 and SSDP discovery strings used for amplification attacks.
